<paragraph blockId="27.[313,1268,691,907]" pageId="27" pageNumber="2239">
<emphasis box="[353,486,787,811]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="2239">Distribution</emphasis>
. Coast of West Africa from 
<collectingCountry box="[827,956,787,811]" name="Mauritania" pageId="27" pageNumber="2239">Mauritania</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry box="[999,1086,787,811]" name="Angola" pageId="27" pageNumber="2239">Angola</collectingCountry>
. Also occurs in subtropical and tropical western Atlantic (Quéro 
<emphasis box="[882,940,819,843]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="2239">et al.</emphasis>
, 1990).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[313,1268,691,907]" pageId="27" pageNumber="2239">
On average about 
<quantity box="[566,702,851,875]" metricMagnitude="6" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="6.1" pageId="27" pageNumber="2239" unit="t" value="6100.0">6100 tonnes</quantity>
of this species are caught in the region each year (
<bibRefCitation author="FAO" box="[324,457,883,907]" pageId="27" pageNumber="2239" refId="ref23310" refString="Four species are likely to be found in the Gulf of Guinea (Shipp, 1981) and two were recorded by Irvine from Ghana. On average about 75 tonnes of triggerfishes are reported to be caught in the region each year (FAO, 2000)." type="book" year="2000">FAO, 2000</bibRefCitation>
), making it an important fishery species in terms of catch.
</paragraph>
